              <div class="guide-section">
                  <h2>HYSA vs Money Market vs CDs vs T-Bills</h2>
                  <p>Choosing the right place to park your cash depends on your goals and when you need the money.</p>

                  <h3>High-Yield Savings Accounts (HYSA)</h3>
                  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Emergency funds and short-term savings.</p>
                  <p>Highly liquid, variable interest rates, easy to set up and transfer funds. No risk to principal as long as it's FDIC-insured.</p>

                  <h3>Money Market Accounts (MMA)</h3>
                  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Large balances where you might need to write a check.</p>
                  <p>Similar to HYSAs but often come with check-writing privileges and debit cards. May require higher minimum balances to get the best APY.</p>

                  <h3>Certificates of Deposit (CDs)</h3>
                  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Money you definitely won't need for a specific period (e.g., saving for a house down payment in 1 year).</p>
                  <p>Locks in a fixed interest rate for a set term (e.g., 6 months, 1 year). If you withdraw early, you'll pay a penalty.</p>

                  <h3>Treasury Bills (T-Bills)</h3>
                  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Taxable accounts in high-tax states.</p>
                  <p>Short-term U.S. government debt obligations. Interest earned is exempt from state and local taxes, making the effective yield higher for many investors.</p>
              </div>

